s spectacular rise to power as a charismatic and savvy politician, to his dramatic presidential campaign. Sugrue looks at Obama's place in the contested history of the civil rights struggle; his views about the root causes of black poverty in America; and the incredible challenges confronting his historic presidency. Does Obama's presidency signal the end of race in American life? In Not Even Past, a leading historian of civil rights, race, and urban America offers a revealing and unflinchingly honest assessment of the culture and politics of race in the age of Obama, and of our prospects for a postracial America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansvBiography. 0aAfrican AmericansxBiography. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rights. 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identity. 0aHistoryvSocial History. 0aPolitical culturexUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aPresidentsxBiographyxUnited States. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aRace relationsxPolitical aspects. 0aRacismvPolitical aspects. 0aRacismxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aRacismxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aRacismzUnited StatesvPolitical aspects. 0aSocial classesvPolitical aspects. 0aSocial classesxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aSocial classesxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aSocial classeszUnited StatesvPolitical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140083419840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400834198423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400834198.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  